State lifting is a design pattern used in React to move the state from higher-level components (like parent or container components) into lower-level components (like child or utility components). This pattern helps to decouple the UI and business logic of your application.
In general, when you see "state" mentioned in relation to React components, it typically refers to the component's internal data that determines its behavior and output. By moving this state up to a parent component, you can avoid passing down large amounts of data through many levels of nested components, which can lead to tight coupling between components and make the code harder to understand and maintain.
The idea behind state lifting is that by keeping the state closer to where it is needed, you reduce the amount of work that needs to be done on each render cycle, as well as making it easier for other components to react to changes in the state. It also allows you to keep more of the UI logic within the component itself rather than having it spread out over multiple layers.
